This is a list of numerals, or symbols for numbers. There is a base-
ten numeral system (commonly called a number system) that uses these 
ten digits to name every possible number. I can't see in what you 
write why it makes a difference to you whether they are called 
numbers or numerals.

>i can not found the numeral or number zero in this system.

The symbol "0" is the numeral zero. Why do you not see it?

>I see the zero nothing, But zero nothing not a number or numeral.
>Zero nothing mean, this is not  a zero. In Arabic language gsifir 
lah.
>this is a system digit,(No value).

You have never explained what you mean by "zero nothing" and whatever 
other kind of zero you have in mind. If you want to talk about a 
distinction, please define it, rather than just using a phrase with 
no meaning.

In mathematics, there is only one quantity called zero, and only one 
symbol "0", although certainly there are different uses (as a digit 
in writing numbers, and as a number used in algebra, for example). 
When we use digits to write a number, each digit is multiplied by the 
value of its place, and therefore is used also as a (symbol for a) 
number. For example, the numeral "123" represents the number 1*100 + 
2*10 + 3*1; the numeral "101" represents "1*100 + 0*10 + 1*1", and 
the "0" means zero tens. Each digit is a symbol for a number.

